result.markdown: --- title: "Homework 1" author: "Jasper Day" date: "6/6/2022" --- # Manipulating Vectors (1D images) ::: {.cell execution_count=1} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using Images ``` ::: ## Make a random vector of length 10: ::: {.cell execution_count=2} ``` {.julia .cell-code} random_vect = rand(10) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=3} ``` 10-element Vector{Float64}: 0.7286408168105528 0.4591391032750355 0.7197863087948619 0.11006406319376294 0.557414702787595 0.26151692428258344 0.904428962212088 0.004947033291061831 0.7212722416623099 0.5585792288593471 ``` ::: ::: ## `mean` and `demean` > Make a function `mean` using a `for` loop, which computes the mean of a vector ::: {.cell execution_count=3} ``` {.julia .cell-code} function mean(x) sumph = 0 for i in x sumph += i end sumph /= length(x) return sumph end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=4} ``` mean (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: ::: Testing our function: ::: {.cell execution_count=4} ``` {.julia .cell-code} @show mean([1,2,3]); ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` mean([1, 2, 3]) = 2.0 ``` ::: ::: > Define `m` to be the mean of `random_vect`: ::: {.cell execution_count=5} ``` {.julia .cell-code} m = mean(random_vect) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=6} ``` 0.5025789385169198 ``` ::: ::: > A new function `demean` takes a vector `x` and subtracts the mean from each value in `x`. ::: {.cell execution_count=6} ``` {.julia .cell-code} function demean(x) return copy(x) .- mean(x) end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=7} ``` demean (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: ::: The mean of `demean(random_vect)` should therefore be 0: ::: {.cell execution_count=7} ``` {.julia .cell-code} mean(demean(random_vect)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=8} ``` 2.2204460492503132e-17 ``` ::: ::: The answer is just about machine $\epsilon$, which is nice. ## `create_bar()` > Generate a vector of 100 zeros. Change the center 20 to 1. ::: {.cell execution_count=8} ``` {.julia .cell-code} function create_bar() barvec = zeros(100) barvec[40:60] .= 1 return barvec end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=9} ``` create_bar (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: ::: ## `vecvec_to_matrix` and the reverse > Write a function that turns a `Vector` of `Vector`s into a matrix: ::: {.cell execution_count=9} ``` {.julia .cell-code} function vecvec_to_matrix(vecvec) tempmat = Matrix{typeof(vecvec[1][1])}(undef, length(vecvec), length(vecvec[1])) for i in 1:length(vecvec) tempmat[:,i] = vecvec[i] end return tempmat end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=10} ``` vecvec_to_matrix (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: ::: And the reverse: ::: {.cell execution_count=10} ``` {.julia .cell-code} function matrix_to_vecvec(matrix) newVec = Vector{Vector{typeof(matrix[1])}}(undef, size(matrix)[2]) for i in 1:size(matrix)[2] newVec[i] = matrix[:,i] end return newVec end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=11} ``` matrix_to_vecvec (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: ::: Testing: ::: {.cell execution_count=11} ``` {.julia .cell-code} @show vecvec_to_matrix([[6 7], [8 9]]); @show matrix_to_vecvec([6 7; 8 9]); ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` vecvec_to_matrix([[6 7], [8 9]]) = [6 8; 7 9] ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` matrix_to_vecvec([6 7; 8 9]) = [[6, 8], [7, 9]] ``` ::: ::: This is the best solution I could find to keep the types consistent. It feels a bit awkward to have to explicitly declare the types, but that's fine. It's also going to be faster than using a mutating function like `push!` or `append!`, since we give the vectors a full size when we create them, so no memory reallocation ever has to occur. Anyway... ## colored_line ::: {.cell execution_count=12} ``` {.julia .cell-code} # Definitions from homework notebook colored_line(x::Vector{<:Real}) = Gray.(Float64.((hcat(x)'))) colored_line(x::Any) = nothing example_vector = [0.5, 0.4, 0.3, 0.2, 0.1, 0.0, 0.7, 0.0, 0.7, 0.9] display(colored_line(example_vector)); ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=13} ``` {.julia .cell-code} display(colored_line(random_vect)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=14} ``` {.julia .cell-code} display(colored_line(create_bar())) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: # Manipulating Images > In this exercise we will get familiar with matrices (2D arrays) in Julia, by manipulating images. > Recall that in Julia images are matrices of `RGB` color objects. > Let's load a picture of Philip again. ::: {.cell execution_count=15} ``` {.julia .cell-code} philip_file = let original = load(download("https://i.imgur.com/VGPeJ6s.jpg")) original[1:8:size(original)[1], 1:8:size(original)[2]] end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=16} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ## `Mean Colors` > Write a function **`mean_colors`** that accepts an object called `image`. It should calculate the mean (average) amounts of red, green and blue in the image and return a tuple `(r, g, b)` of those means. ::: {.cell execution_count=16} ``` {.julia .cell-code} function mean_colors(image) avgrgb = sum(philip_file) ./ length(philip_file) # Honestly you could stop here. Not sure why this all needs to be a whole function. return (avgrgb.r, avgrgb.b, avgrgb.b) end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=17} ``` mean_colors (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: ::: ## Quantizing numbers > Look up the documentation on the `floor` function. Use it to write a function `quantize(x::Number)` that takes in a value $x$ (which you can assume is between 0 and 1) and "quantizes" it into bins of width 0.1. For example, check that 0.267 gets mapped to 0.2. ::: {.cell execution_count=17} ``` {.julia .cell-code} quantize(x::Number) = floor(10x)/10 @show quantize(0.267) @show quantize(0.91) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` quantize(0.267) = 0.2 quantize(0.91) = 0.9 ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=18} ``` 0.9 ``` ::: ::: ## A second method: > Write the second **method** of the function `quantize`, i.e. a new *version* of the function with the *same* name. This method will accept a color object called `color`, of the type `AbstractRGB`. The method you write should return a new `RGB` object, in which each component ($r$, $g$ and $b$) are quantized. ::: {.cell execution_count=18} ``` {.julia .cell-code} quantize(x::AbstractRGB) = RGB(quantize(x.r), quantize(x.g), quantize(x.b)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=19} ``` quantize (generic function with 2 methods) ``` ::: ::: ## A third method: > Write a method `quantize(image::AbstractMatrix)` that quantizes an image by quantizing each pixel in the image. (You may assume that the matrix is a matrix of color objects.) ::: {.cell execution_count=19} ``` {.julia .cell-code} quantize(image::AbstractMatrix) = quantize.(image) display(quantize(philip_file)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: It surprisingly looks prety good, despite having half the color bandwidth of the original photo. With 10 buckets, though, you can definitely see some artefacting on the walls. Let's try larger buckets: ::: {.cell execution_count=20} ``` {.julia .cell-code} quantize(x::Number, buckets::Integer) = floor(buckets*x)/buckets quantize(x::AbstractRGB, buckets::Integer) = RGB(quantize(x.r, buckets), quantize(x.g, buckets), quantize(x.b, buckets)) quantize(image::AbstractMatrix, buckets::Integer) = quantize.(image, buckets) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=21} ``` quantize (generic function with 6 methods) ``` ::: ::: Here's Philip with 5 buckets: ::: {.cell execution_count=21} ``` {.julia .cell-code} display(quantize(philip_file, 5)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: Pretty exciting. I like the obvious lines in the shadow. 2 buckets: ::: {.cell execution_count=22} ``` {.julia .cell-code} display(quantize(philip_file, 2)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: Most of the picture is taken up by the rather bland `RGB(0.5,0.5,0.5)`. I liked 5 buckets better, I think. ## Color inversion > Write a function `invert` that inverts a color, i.e. sends $(r, g, b)$ to $(1 - r, 1-g, 1-b)$. ::: {.cell execution_count=23} ``` {.julia .cell-code} invert(x::AbstractRGB) = RGB(1-x.r, 1-x.g, 1-x.b) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=24} ``` invert (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: ::: Jeez man. Playing around with color inversion: ::: {.cell execution_count=24} ``` {.julia .cell-code} black = RGB(0.0,0.0,0.0) invert(black) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=25} ![](Homework_1_files/figure-html/cell-25-output-1.svg){} ::: ::: It's white. ::: {.cell execution_count=25} ``` {.julia .cell-code} invert.(philip_file) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=26} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: He looks rather ectoplasmic. The shadow in the background now reveals its secrets: it's floorboards all the way back! ## Noisify > Write a function `noisify(x::Number, s)` to add randomness of intensity $s$ to a value $x$, i.e. to add a random value between $-s$ and $+s$ to $x$. If the result falls outside the range $(0, 1)$ you should "clamp" it to that range. (Note that Julia has a `clamp` function, but you should write your own function `myclamp(x)`.) ::: {.cell execution_count=26} ``` {.julia .cell-code} using Distributions ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` WARNING: using Distributions.mean in module Main conflicts with an existing identifier. ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=27} ``` {.julia .cell-code} myclamp(x::Number) = x>1 ? 1 : (x<0 ? 0 : x) noisifyp(x::Number, s) = myclamp(x + 2s*(rand()-0.5)) # That ^ works but I don't like it. noisify(x::Number, s) = myclamp(x + rand(Uniform(-s,s))) # I like that a little more but it may actually be slower. noisifyp(x::AbstractRGB, s) = RGB(noisifyp(x.r, s), noisifyp(x.g, s), noisifyp(x.b, s)) noisify(x::AbstractRGB, s) = RGB(noisify(x.r, s), noisify(x.g, s), noisify(x.b, s)) noisifyp(x::AbstractMatrix, s) = noisifyp.(x, s) noisify(x::AbstractMatrix, s) = noisify.(x, s); ``` ::: Interestingly, the story of the two different noisifies appears to be a story of making a solution *worse* in an attempt to make it more elegant. It's much worse, apparently, to take a random number from a uniform distribution across the desired range than to simply multiply `rand()` to change it into the desired range. Probably this is because the `rand(Uniform(-s, s))` calls two different functions, and who knows how optimized the function for the uniform distribution is. `rand()`, on the other hand, can be super optimized, so the multiplication and subtraction doesn't add too much cost. I found that `noisifyp` on the picture of Philip, with a noise level of 1, tended to run in 4 seconds or less, even with 8% compilation time. The best I could get out of `noisify` was 4.3 seconds, with upper bounds closer to 5 seconds. Sometimes the clunkier solution is actually faster. The image is still (barely) recognizable with a noise level of 10: ::: {.cell execution_count=28} ``` {.julia .cell-code} noisifyp(philip_file, 10) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=29} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: It becomes completely unrecognizable at a noise level of 20, though. ::: {.cell execution_count=29} ``` {.julia .cell-code} noisifyp(philip_file, 20) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=30} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: Although you can still just barely make out where the eyes are supposed to be, at least if you already knew it. By the way, here is Grant's (much better) definition of decimate (see mine [here](ManipulatingImages.qmd#decimate)): ::: {.cell execution_count=30} ``` {.julia .cell-code} decimate(image, ratio=5) = image[1:ratio:end, 1:ratio:end] ``` ::: {#decimate .cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=31} ``` decimate (generic function with 2 methods) ``` ::: ::: # Convolutions > As we have seen in the videos, we can produce cool effects using the mathematical technique of >**convolutions**. We input one image $M$ and get a new image $M'$ back. > > Conceptually we think of $M$ as a matrix. In practice, in Julia it will be a `Matrix` of color objects, and we may need to take that into account. Ideally, however, we should write a **generic** function that will work for any type of data contained in the matrix. > > A convolution works on a small **window** of an image, i.e. a region centered around a given point $(i, j)$. We will suppose that the window is a square region with odd side length $2\ell + 1$, running from $-\ell, \ldots, 0, \ldots, \ell$. > > The result of the convolution over a given window, centred at the point $(i, j)$ is a *single number*; this number is the value that we will use for $M'_{i, j}$. > (Note that neighbouring windows overlap.) > > To get started let's restrict ourselves to convolutions in 1D. > So a window is just a 1D region from $-\ell$ to $\ell$. > Let's create a vector `v` of random numbers of length `n=100`. ::: {.cell execution_count=31} ``` {.julia .cell-code} n = 100 v = rand(n) colored_line(v) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=32} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ## Boundary conditions > We need to decide how to handle the **boundary conditions**, i.e. what happens if we try to access a position in the vector `v` beyond `1:n`. The simplest solution is to assume that $v_{i}$ is 0 outside the original vector; however, this may lead to strange boundary effects. > A better solution is to use the *closest* value that is inside the vector. Effectively we are extending the vector and copying the extreme values into the extended positions. (Indeed, this is one way we could implement this; these extra positions are called **ghost cells**.) > Write a function `extend(v, i)` that checks whether the position $i$ is inside `1:n`. If so, return the $i$th component of `v`; otherwise, return the nearest end value. ::: {.cell execution_count=32} ``` {.julia .cell-code} extend(v, i) = i in 1:length(v) ? v[i] : (i < 1 ? first(v) : last(v)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=33} ``` extend (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: ::: ## 1D blur > Write a function `blur_1D(v, l)` that blurs a vector `v` with a window of length `l` by averaging the elements within a window from $-\ell$ to $\ell$. This is called a **box blur**. ::: {.cell execution_count=33} ``` {.julia .cell-code} blur_1D(v,l) = [sum([extend(v,j + i) for j in -l:l]) / (2l + 1) for i in 1:length(v)] # Look how sexy. One line. No silly functions like "copy." I liiiike it. Even though all it can do is the box average :) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=34} ``` blur_1D (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: ::: In $\text{\LaTeX}$, that line of code translates to: $$ v'_i = \frac{\sum_{j = -\ell}^{\ell}v_{j+i}}{2\ell+1} $$ Not sure if that makes it any clearer. ::: {.cell execution_count=34} ``` {.julia .cell-code} colored_line(example_vector) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=35} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=35} ``` {.julia .cell-code} colored_line(blur_1D(example_vector, 2)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=36} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: You can tell that the dark spots still exist under the box blur, but there's no purely black spots left. Generally the gradient is softer across the vector. ## Different size box_blurs No interactive controls here. Just a couple of well-chosen examples. ::: {.cell execution_count=36} ``` {.julia .cell-code} l_box = 0 colored_line(blur_1D(v,l_box)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=37} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=37} ``` {.julia .cell-code} l_box = 2 colored_line(blur_1D(v,l_box)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=38} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=38} ``` {.julia .cell-code} l_box = 4 colored_line(blur_1D(v,l_box)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=39} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=39} ``` {.julia .cell-code} l_box = 10 colored_line(blur_1D(v,l_box)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=40} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: By 10, the whole vector is basically just gray. ## General 1D Convolutions > The box blur is a simple example of a **convolution**, i.e. a linear function of a window around each point, given by > $$ v'_{i} = \sum_{n}\,v_{i - n}\,k_{n} $$ > > where $k$ is a vector called a **kernel**. > > Again, we need to take care about what happens if $v_{i -n }$ falls off the end of the vector. > > Write a function `convolve_vector(v, k)` that performs this convolution. You need to think of the vector $k$ as being *centred* on the position $i$. So $n$ in the above formula runs between $-\ell$ and $\ell$, where $2\ell + 1$ is the length of the vector $k$. You will need to do the necessary manipulation of indices. ::: {.cell execution_count=40} ``` {.julia .cell-code} convolve_vector(v,k) = [sum([extend(v,i-(n-1 - length(k)2)) * k[n] # assume k is not an offset matrix for n in 1:length(k)]) for i in 1:length(v)] ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=41} ``` convolve_vector (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: ::: Also neatly fits into (almost) one line. I like Julia more and more the more I use it. Although my obsession with single-line functions is somewhat to the detriment of the readability of my code. ::: {.cell execution_count=41} ``` {.julia .cell-code} test_convolution = let v = [1, 10, 100, 1000, 10000] k = [2, 1, 0, 1, 3] convolve_vector(v, k) end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=42} ``` 5-element Vector{Int64}: 214 2104 21013 30130 31300 ``` ::: ::: :::{.callout-note} When using $\sum_{n}\,v_{i - n}\,k_{n}$, the kernel is basically flipped 180. You can avoid this behavior by using $\sum_{n}\,v_{i + n}\,k_{n}$, but [you shouldn't.](Convolutions.qmd#polynomial-multiplication) ::: ## Gaussian kernel The definition of a Gaussian kernel in 1D is: $$ G(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi \sigma^2}} \exp\left({\frac{-x^2}{2\sigma^2}}\right) $$ > We need to **sample** (evaluate) this at each pixel in a rigion of size $n^2$, and then **normalize** so that the sum of the resulting kernel is 1. :::{.callout-note} Rather than taking $\sigma=1$ for simplicity, I chose to allow any value of $\sigma$. Also, there seems to be a typo in the instructions. We should be evaluating over $2n+1$, not $n^2$. ::: ::: {.cell execution_count=42} ``` {.julia .cell-code} normalize(v) = [v[i] / sum(v) for i in 1:length(v)] function gaussian_kernel(n::Integer, =1) G(x) = 1/(2*^2) * exp(-x^2/(2^2)) new_vec = zeros(n) [new_vec[i] = G(i-1 - n2) for i in 1:n] return normalize(new_vec) end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=43} ``` gaussian_kernel (generic function with 2 methods) ``` ::: ::: Seems to work. ::: {.cell execution_count=43} ``` {.julia .cell-code} gaussian_kernel_size_1D = 5 test_gauss_1D_a = let v = rand(20) k = gaussian_kernel(gaussian_kernel_size_1D) if k !== missing convolve_vector(v, k) end end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=44} ``` 20-element Vector{Float64}: 0.3306104370469224 0.4167421213105778 0.42051062450749477 0.34689528825780236 0.31026731328014334 0.3880559710150231 0.5746657392142583 0.596419797784882 0.47205925205934157 0.4781074298864467 0.48891366269665415 0.46614600396485906 0.4583874090277395 0.4461292232391669 0.35440711462022645 0.3197213893549098 0.3238643086402708 0.29193508661111545 0.36203427593319215 0.5579598661834908 ``` ::: ::: You can get some very pretty gradients by increasing the standard deviation of the gaussian kernel. For example: ::: {.cell execution_count=44} ``` {.julia .cell-code} nice_gradient = let v = rand(20) k = gaussian_kernel(10, 2) convolve_vector(v,k) end colored_line(nice_gradient) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=45} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: # Convolutions of Images With 2D images, the convolution is given by a **kernel matrix** $K$: $$ M'_{i,j} = \sum_{k,l} \, M_{i-k,j-l} \, K_{k,l} $$ where the sum is over the possible values of $k$ and $l$ in the window. The window is centered at $(i,j)$. The convolution is often notated with a star $*$: $$ M' = M * K $$ ## Extend_matrix: > Write a function extend_mat that takes a matrix M and indices i and j, and returns the closest element of the matrix. ::: {.cell execution_count=45} ``` {.julia .cell-code} extend_mat(M::AbstractMatrix, i, j) = M[clamp(i, 1, size(M)[1]), clamp(j, 1, size(M)[2])]; ``` ::: Let's extend Philip: ::: {.cell execution_count=46} ``` {.julia .cell-code} let philip_head = philip_file[250:430,110:230] [extend_mat(philip_head, i, j) for (i,j) in Iterators.product(-50:size(philip_head,1)+51, (-50:size(philip_head,2)+51))] end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=47} ```{=html} ``` ::: ::: More single line functions. Are they beautiful or annoying? That's your choice. Now (finally!) the meat of the first homework: ## `Convolve_image` > Implement a function convolve_image(M, K). ::: {.cell execution_count=47} ``` {.julia .cell-code} function convolve_image(M::AbstractMatrix, K::AbstractMatrix) NewMat = zeros(size(M)) adjustx = size(K)[1] 2 + 1 adjusty = size(K)[2] 2 + 1 for (i,j) in Iterators.product(1:size(M)[1], 1:size(M)[2]) ## for each M_{i,j} NewMat[i,j] = sum([ extend_mat(M, i-k - adjustx, j-l - adjusty) .* K[k,l] for (k,l) in Iterators.product(1:size(K)[1], 1:size(K)[2]) ]) end return NewMat end ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=48} ``` convolve_image (generic function with 1 method) ``` ::: :::
